  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Vincent's Word Studies",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Zeal (ζῆλον)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Read πόνον labor, which occurs elsewhere only in Revelation 16:10, Revelation 16:11; Revelation 21:4, in the sense of pain. Πονος labor is from the root of πένομαι to work for one's daily bread, and thence to be poor. Πόνος toil, πένης one who works for his daily bread, and πονηρός wicked, have a common root. See on wickedness, Mark 7:22. In their original conceptions, κόπος labor (1 Corinthians 15:58; 2 Corinthians 6:5) emphasizes the fatigue of labor: μόχθος hard labor (2 Corinthians 11:27; 1 Thessalonians 2:9), the hardship: πόνος the effort, but πόνος has passed, in the New Testament, in every instance but this, into the meaning of pain.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Read πόνον labor, which occurs elsewhere only in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Revelation 16:10",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Revelation 16:11",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Revelation 21:4",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", in the sense of pain. Πονος labor is from the root of πένομαι to work for one's daily bread, and thence to be poor. Πόνος toil, πένης one who works for his daily bread, and πονηρός wicked, have a common root. See on wickedness, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Mark 7:22",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". In their original conceptions, κόπος labor (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1 Corinthians 15:58",
            "children": []
